 road  which  passes  to  the  south.    Recently  upgraded  four  wheel  drive  tracks  give 
 access to the tenement.  The topography is generally rugged. 
 The  climate  of  the  project  area  is  semi  arid  with  a  mean  annual  rainfall  of  about

 September is in the range 7.5ºC to 12.8ºC.

text:
The  corridor-like  structure  was  tested  on  Images  ground  by  a  scout  inclined  RAB 
 drilling programme during October 2002.  
 Twelve holes were drilled for a total of 887m, comprising 467m of blade and 420m of 
 Blade drilling easily penetrated the soft weathered zone of the bedrock profile, but on 
 encountering fresh rock required changeover to hammer drilling. 
 Assays returned a few low-order gold results associated with narrow limonitic quartz 
 stringer  zones  in  holes  2  and  6.    Attempts  to  cross-section  the  data  suggested  the 
 stringer  zones  might  be  caught  up  in  drag  fold  structures,  producing  a  patchy 
 distribution of grades and widths along both strike and dip. 
 To  assist  in  determining  if  further  commitment  of  infill  drilling  was  warranted,  a 
 limited  RC  drilling  programme  was  undertaken  to  test  the  depth  extent  of  the 
 mineralisation encountered.. 
 GEOLOGICAL SETTING 
 REGIONAL GEOLOGICAL SETTING 
 The  tenement  covers  the  eastern  end  of  the  Archaean  Mosquito  Creek  Formation 
 sediments directly to the east it is overlain by the Proterozoic Kylena Basalts. 
 The Mosquito Creek formation comprises interbedded greywackes, siltstone, shales, 
 sandstone, conglomerates, occasional chert bands and intrusive igneous sills.  These 
 rocks have been tightly folded into an east-west trending syncline outcropping as a 
 belt approximately 130km long by 55km wide.

 MT HAYS PROJECT GEOLOGICAL SETTING  
 Within the Mt Hays Project area the Western Anomaly prospect had originally been 
 identified  in  2002  by  soil  sampling  as  a  narrow,  East  West  trending  Au  and  As 
 anomaly of about 1.5km in length.  Subsequent mapping indicated that the anomalous 
 zone appeared to be related to swarms of small deformed quartz veins intruded into 
 folded  and  cleaved  shaly  turbidites  of  the  Archaean  Mosquito  Creek  Formation.

 SAMPLING METHOD AND APPROACH 
 For  the  stream  samples  suitable  trap  sites  were  selected  and  approximately  3kg  of 
 roughly  sieved  sample  was  collected  for  later  drying  and  sizing  by  Genalysis 
 Laboratory Services at their Perth laboratory. 
 For  the  soil  samples  sites  were  selected  on  a  rough  grid  pattern  around  a  trend  of 
 quartz  veining  and  approximately  3kg  of  roughly  sieved  sample  was  collected  for 
 later drying and sizing by Genalysis Laboratory Services at their Perth laboratory.
